 with US regulators. Earlier this year Morgan Stanleypaid $249 =0Amillion o=
f fines =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2024-01-16/morgan-st=
anley-leaked-some-block-trades=3Fcmpid=3DBBD101624_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3D=
email&utm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D241016&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=
=0A for leaking block trades. Bad, don=E2=80=99t do that.=0A=0ABut you migh=
t expect the bank to suffer another punishment for doing this. The =0Acusto=
mers who did the block trades =E2=80=94 the private equity firms who swore =
the =0Abanks to secrecy =E2=80=94 will be pretty annoyed. The bank betrayed=
 them, ignored =0Atheir explicit instructions, and cost them money. These c=
ustomers are often =0Arepeat players: not random individuals selling one bl=
ock of stock once, butbig =0Aprivate equity firms =0A<https://www.bloomberg=
.com/news/articles/2024-01-16/blackstone-oaktree-burned-by-morgan-stanley-=
s-block-trade-leaks=3Fcmpid=3DBBD101624_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_s=
ource=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D241016&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A that do =
these trades regularly. You might expect a bank that leaks block =0Atrades =
to be put in the =E2=80=9Cpenalty box,=E2=80=9D where the private equity fi=
rm won=E2=80=99t do =0Atrades with it for a while as punishment.=0A=0AOr yo=
u might not. My usual assumption is (1) memories in financial markets are =
=0Avery short and (2) every customer sort of assumes that every bank is up =
to no =0Agood, so avoiding one bank because you caught it leaking block tra=
des will just =0Alead you to deal with other banks that you haven=E2=80=99t=
 caught yet.=0A=0ABut here=E2=80=99s a Wall Street Journal story =0A<https:=
//www.wsj.com/finance/bank-of-america-is-losing-work-over-block-trading-pro=
be-in-asia-8d076e84=3Fmod=3Ditp_wsj>=0A from last week about the block-trad=
e penalty box:=0A=0AAllegations that Bank of America employees in India sha=
red nonpublic =0Ainformation with investors ahead of stock sales are costin=
g the bank business.=0A=0APrivate-equity firm EQT pulled the bank from a ma=
ndate for an upcoming initial =0Apublic offering of a student-loan company,=
 according to people familiar with =0Athe matter. A Norwegian conglomerate =
planning to take an Indian subsidiary =0Apublic also has concerns about wor=
king with the bank because of the =0Aallegations, some of the people said.=
=0A=0AThe Wall Street Journal reported in September that Bank of America wa=
s =0Ainvestigating whether bankers in Asia shared nonpublic information wit=
h =0Ainvestors ahead of stock sales. The probe was launched after a whistle=
blower =0Acomplaint alleged bankers had done so before a stock sale in Indi=
a this spring.=0A=0AFrom first principles you might think that getting a ba=
d reputation with =0Aclients would beworse, for a bank, than annoying regul=
ators. Sometimes that =0Amight even be true.=0A=0A=0ACell phones=0A=0AI use=
d to get a lot of reader email proposing weird insider trading =0Ahypotheti=
cals. I guess I still do. But now my most reliable funny reader-email =0Ahy=
potheticals are about the US Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=99scr=
ackdown =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2023-02-02/the-sec-w=
ants-to-see-more-phones=3Fcmpid=3DBBD101624_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&u=
tm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D241016&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A on f=
inancial-industry employees talking about work on =E2=80=9Cunofficial chann=
els=E2=80=9D =0Alike WhatsApp or texts from their personal phones. Here=E2=
=80=99s a good one:=0A=0AOn LinkedIn, I saw that an old coworker reached 17=
 years at his job. I texted =0Ahim to say, "happy 17 years!", to which he r=
esponded, "please don't text my =0Apersonal device regarding work", obvious=
ly fearful of the SEC fines. He's =0Aprobably right, but it got me thinking=
, if I had replied on LinkedIn instead, =0Awouldn't that also be a covered =
communication in the SEC's eyes=3F What if I =0Areact to the message with a=
 thumbs up emoji=3F I guess that's probably crime. =0AAnyway, I thought you=
 might appreciate this.=0A=0AI did! I suspect that congratulating someone o=
n a work anniversary is not the =0Asort of =E2=80=9Ccommunication about bus=
iness matters=E2=80=9D that has to be kept to official =0Achannels, though =
it is not unambiguous. (What if a client, or potential client, =0Ahad sent =
that text=3F Could the guy then reply =E2=80=9Cthanks, great to hear from y=
ou=3F=E2=80=9D =0AWhen does it cross from small talk to client relationship=
 management=3F)=0A=0AAnd, somewhat bizarrely, it seems like LinkedIn is not=
 the sort of official =0Achannel that you=E2=80=99re allowed to use to talk=
 about work; the SEC haspreviously =0Afined a bank =0A<https://www.bloomber=
g.com/opinion/articles/2023-08-08/don-t-do-deals-on-linkedin=3Fcmpid=3DBBD1=
01624_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D2410=
16&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A because its employees sent each other Link=
edIn messages. So, yes, if you work =0Ain finance, clicking a thumbs-up emo=
ji on a potential client=E2=80=99s work anniversary =0Apost is =E2=80=A6 bo=
y is this not legal advice, but maybe check with compliance before =0Ayou d=
o that=3F The law is so weird.=0A=0A=0AThings happen=0A=0AMorgan Stanley =
